===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|day|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|dæg|dæġ|day|lang=ang|sc=Latinx}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*dagaz||day}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*dʰegʷʰ-||to burn}}. Cognate with {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|dei||day|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|dag||day|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Tag||day|lang=de}}, Swedish and Danish {{term|dag||day|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|dagur||day|lang=is}}. Compare {{etyl|sq|-}} {{term|djeg||to burn|lang=sq}}, {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|degti||to burn|lang=lt}}, {{etyl|xto|-}} {{term|tsäk-|lang=xto}}, {{etyl|ru|-}} {{term|жечь|tr=žeč’|lang=ru|sc=Cyrl}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term|दाह||heat|tr=dāha|lang=sa|sc=Deva}}, {{term|दहति||to burn|tr=dahati|lang=sa|sc=Deva}}.

Latin {{term/t|la|diēs}} (from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*dyew-||to shine}}) is a [[false cognate]].

